Part 0: Correcting more misconceptions

Previously, I thought that questions were assigned to a cluster based on the model fit to the \(U\) matrix, and that the corresponding answers were assigned to the same cluster. There was some ambiguous wording in the original paper about this that I misinterpreted.

Justine + the source code have confirmed that K-means is applied to \(U_{A}\) and \(U_{Q}\) separately. They are not necessarily dependent, although the questions are projected into the answer space to form \(U_{Q}\). So a question of type 1 could receive an answer of type 2. In my analysis of model output (coming separately), I will examine this.

Part 1: Choose rank for SVD

We use the SVD reduced from 251 to 250.

Note: snipping only applies to the \(U\) matrix (left singular), not to the \(\Sigma\) matrix.

(a) Elbow plot of singular values

# Load data
Sigma_250 <- np$loadtxt("prompt_types_matrix_objs/Sigma_rank_250_nosnip.npy.gz")

Sigma_250 <- data.frame(singular_values=Sigma_250)

summary(Sigma_250)

##  Mean   :0.9826  
##  3rd Qu.:1.0355  
##  Max.   :2.0834
plot_singular_values <- function(df, n) {
  df <- df %>% slice(., 1:n)
  ggp <- ggplot(df,
         aes(x=as.integer(rownames(df)), 
             y=singular_values)
         ) + 
      geom_point() + ggtitle(paste0("Plot of the first ", n, " singular values")) +
    xlab("Index") + ylab("Singular value") +
    geom_line() 
  
  print(ggp)
}


plot_singular_values(Sigma_250, n=50)

plot_singular_values(Sigma_250, n=nrow(Sigma_250))

Interpretation: Choose \(rank=50\) because the large plateau in the plot is around singular value 50.

(b) Explained variance plot

explained_var_250 <- np$loadtxt("prompt_types_matrix_objs/ExplainedVariance__rank_250_nosnip.npy.gz")

explained_var_250 <- data.frame(explained_variance=explained_var_250)

plot_explained_variance <- function(df) {
  ggp <- ggplot(df,
         aes(x=as.integer(rownames(df)), 
             y=explained_variance)
         ) + 
      geom_point() + ggtitle(paste0("Explained variance by each of ", length(df$explained_variance), " singular values")) +
    xlab("Index") + ylab("Variance") +
    geom_line() 
  
  print(ggp)
}

plot_explained_variance(explained_var_250)

Note: It is strange that the first singular value does not explain the most variance. Maybe this is an argument for snipping the first dimension?

Justine said that snipping the first dimension is done because empirically the first dimension tends to correspond with high frequency features.

(c) Cumulative explained variance plot

plot_cumulative_variance_explained <- function(df) {
  df$cumulative_variance <- cumsum(df$explained_variance)
  ggp <- ggplot(df,
         aes(x=as.integer(rownames(df)), 
             y=cumulative_variance)
         ) + 
      geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
    ggtitle(paste0("Cumulative variance explained by ", length(df$explained_variance), " components")) +
    xlab("Index") + ylab("Variance") +
    geom_line() 
  
  print(ggp)
}

plot_cumulative_variance_explained(explained_var_250)

Interpretation: Unclear; maybe 30% of variance explained by first ~50 components, and 50% of variance explained by first ~100 components. We are leaving out a lot of variance by reducing rank. But maybe that variance is noise?

Upshot: Let’s try reducing rank to 50 and compare that with unreduced SVD.

Part 2: Choosing k based on BIC for the unreduced matrix

Legend of GMM types

  • E = “univariate, equal variance”,
  • V = “univariate, unequal variance”,
  • EII = “spherical, equal volume”,
  • VII = “spherical, varying volume”,
  • EEI = “diagonal, equal volume and shape”,
  • VEI = “diagonal, equal shape”,
  • EVI = “diagonal, equal volume, varying shape”,
  • VVI = “diagonal, varying volume and shape”,
  • EEE = “ellipsoidal, equal volume, shape and orientation”,
  • EVE = “ellipsoidal, equal volume and orientation”,
  • VEE = “ellipsoidal, equal shape and orientation”,
  • VVE = “ellipsoidal, equal orientation”,
  • EEV = “ellipsoidal, equal volume and shape”,
  • VEV = “ellipsoidal, equal shape”

Full list: https://mclust-org.github.io/mclust/reference/mclustModelNames.html

Note: The procedure automatically tries to fit all of the possible models, but I drop the model types that have BIC=NA anywhere.

(a) Choosing k on the unreduced* matrix, no snipping

generate_bics_plot <- function(U_prompt_norm, max_components=20) {
  
  gmm <- densityMclust(U_prompt_norm, G = seq(1,max_components,1))
  rank <- ncol(U_prompt_norm)

  print(summary(gmm))

  print("")
  print("")
  print(paste("Best BIC: ", gmm$bic))
  
  BIC_df <- as.data.frame(gmm$BIC[,]) %>% select_if(~ !any(is.na(.)))
  
  model_names <- colnames(BIC_df)
  BIC_df$num_components <- rownames(BIC_df)
  data_long <- gather(BIC_df, GMM_type, BIC, model_names, factor_key=TRUE)
  data_long$num_components <- as.integer(data_long$num_components)

  ggp <- ggplot(data_long, aes(x=num_components, y=BIC, group=GMM_type)) + 
  geom_point(aes(shape=GMM_type, color=GMM_type)) +
  geom_line(aes(color=GMM_type)) +
  ggtitle(paste("BIC and number of components in Gaussian mixture models, rank =", rank)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = min(25, max(data_long$num_components))
                                                    ))
  
  print(ggp)
  print("Full BIC results:")
  
  return(
    BIC_df %>%
  kable() %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"),
                full_width=FALSE) %>%
  scroll_box(height = "350px")
  )
}

U_prompt_norm <- np$loadtxt("prompt_types_matrix_objs/U_prompt_norm_rank_250_nosnip.npy.gz")

Conclusions

  • snipping first dimension seems to make no difference to rank reduction.
  • possible candidate for rank reduction = 50.
  • BIC decreases monotonically so we still don’t know how to choose k.
  • BIC trends do not seem to vary with rank reduction.
